1. Problem specification
Given a positive integer n, produce an ordered sequence of length n mapping each integer i from 1 to n to a string as follows:
- If i is divisible by 3 and not by 5, output "Fizz".
- If i is divisible by 5 and not by 3, output "Buzz".
- If i is divisible by both 3 and 5, output "FizzBuzz".
- Otherwise output the decimal representation of i.
The sequence must be deterministic and reproducible for identical inputs.

2. Input validation rules
- Accept a single input parameter n representing the number of items to produce.
- Validate that n is an integer: use Number.isInteger(n).
- Validate that n is within an allowed range: n > 0. If a maximum is required, choose an implementation limit (example: n <= 1_000_000) to prevent resource exhaustion; when exceeded throw RangeError.
- On invalid type (non-number) or non-integer, throw TypeError or return an explicit error object as per host API conventions.
- On out-of-range integer, throw RangeError with message describing allowed range.

3. Output format and mapping rules
- Return an Array of strings of length n where array index 0 corresponds to i = 1.
- Each element must be the exact strings: "Fizz", "Buzz", "FizzBuzz" or the decimal string of the number with no extra whitespace or punctuation.
- Preserve order: element at index (i-1) corresponds to i.

4. Efficient generation algorithm
- Prefer single-pass iteration from 1 to n, computing divisibility using modular arithmetic: i % 3 === 0 and i % 5 === 0.
- For memory-constrained environments, support generator-based streaming APIs that yield each string on demand instead of building the full array.
- Optimization: compute both divisibility tests per iteration and avoid repeated string concatenation. Use precomputed constants for 3 and 5 where helpful.
- Time complexity: O(n). Space complexity: O(n) for full-array implementation, O(1) auxiliary.

5. Edge cases and behaviour for non-integers and out-of-range values
- Non-integer numbers: reject via Number.isInteger; if accepted, define behaviour explicitly (e.g., floor to integer or throw). Recommended: throw TypeError.
- Zero and negative numbers: treat as invalid; throw RangeError.
- Extremely large n: enforce application limit and throw RangeError when exceeded. Document memory/time implications and suggest streaming.
- Non-number inputs: throw TypeError.

